\begin_layout Section
Moral Hazard Terminology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There two types of moral hazard:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
ex ante
\shape default
 moral hazard: Given that an agent is insured, the agent will not take costly
 steps to reduce the probability of losses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape italic
ex post
\shape default
 moral hazard: Given that an agent suffers a loss and the agent's insurance
 company pays a portion of the loss, the agent will over-consume.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the model we will look at this week, an agent chooses an action (which
 is costly for the agent) that influences the 
\shape italic
probability
\shape default
 of a good outcome.
 Principal does not observe the action, but does observe the outcome; which
 is where the information asymmetry comes from.
 Therefore, the principal can condition payment on the outcome, but this
 will not get us to the 
\shape italic
first best
\shape default
.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

First best
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as defined in Section Note 9, Full Information (First Degree Price Discriminati
on).
 Recall my explanation for why we call the full information case as the
 first best.
 If this is unclear, review Lecture Note 15.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Further assume that the principal is risk neutral and the agent is risk
 averse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key to understanding moral hazard models is to note that there is a
 trade-off from the perspective of the risk neutral principal: to incentivize
 the agent to put in more effort by varying the wages according to an observable
 (or contractible; or verifiable) variable which is 
\shape italic
not perfectly correlated 
\shape default
with effort; and to provide some insurance such that the risk averse agent's
 individual rationality constraint is satisfied.
 In other words, if an agent bears risk because there exists noise with
 regards to the observable variable (quantity below), the agent will have
 to be paid a higher (expected) wage to achieve its reservation utility
 (in other words, for the Individual Rationality Constraint to hold).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Principal-Agent with 3 Actions and 2 Outcomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
A firm hires a scientist to develop a new product.
 The scientist can choose a level of 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in\left\{ e_{l},\, e_{m},\, e_{h}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{l}<e_{m}<e_{h}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The model would be more realistic if the scientist's choice set was continuous
 and we could solve by setting up the optimization problem and the corresponding
 Lagrangian.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and gets a wage 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 The scientist's utility is additive and is written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula \[
u(e,w)=\ln w-c(e),\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c(e_{l})=0$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $c(e_{m})=1$
\end_inset

; and 
\begin_inset Formula $c(e_{h})=2$
\end_inset

.
 The reservation utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{u}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is normalized and equal to zero (0) and known by both the principal and
 the agent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
There are two possible outcomes:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A more general model would have a continuous set of outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 a good outcome (the scientist invents a widget) denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{G}$
\end_inset

 and a bad outcome (the scientist fails to invent a widget) denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that the probability of a good outcome given the level of effort
 are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\Pr(x_{G}|e_{l}) & \equiv & p_{l}=\frac{1}{10}\\
\Pr(x_{G}|e_{m}) & \equiv & p_{m}=\frac{1}{2}\\
\Pr(x_{G}|e_{h}) & \equiv & p_{h}=\frac{2}{3}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Note that the probability of the good outcome is increasing in the level
 of effort, or higher effort levels first order stochastically dominate
 (FOSD) lower effort levels.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Check that this is in fact the case by drawing the cdfs for each level of
 effort.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Revenue to the firm is equal to 12 if the outcome is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{G}$
\end_inset

 and 0 otherwise.
 With a slight abuse of notation, let's say that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{G}=12$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{B}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\shape italic
The principal has bargaining power and so can set the contract
\shape default
.
 Recall that if the principal has full bargaining power, then 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the agent always receive her reservation utility level, and Pareto comparison
 between contracts depends only on the principal's utility that is induced
 by those contracts.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
